[[Image:spacetime_curvature.png|thumb|right|300px|Two-dimensional analogy of space-time distortion described in General Relativity.]]

The '''theory of relativity''', or simply '''relativity''', refers specifically to two theories: [[Albert Einstein]]'s [[special relativity]] and [[general relativity]].  

The term "relativity" was coined by [[Max Planck]] in [[1908]] to emphasize how special relativity (and later, general relativity) uses the [[principle of relativity]].

== Special relativity ==
{{main|Special relativity}}

[[Albert Einstein]]'s [[1905]] paper "[[Annus Mirabilis Papers#Papers|On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies]]" introduced the ''special theory of relativity''. Special relativity considers that observers in [[inertial reference frame]]s, which are in uniform motion relative to one another, cannot perform any experiment to determine which one of them is "stationary". This is actually [[Galileo Galilei|Galileo]]'s [[principle of relativity]]; Einstein's contribution was to explicitly include [[electromagnetism]] within this principle, which required that the [[Galilean transformation]]s be replaced by the [[Lorentz transformation]]s.  The resultant theory has many surprising consequences. In particular, it requires that the [[speed of light]] in a [[vacuum]] be the same for all these observers, regardless of their motion, or the motion of the source of the [[light]], since the invariance of the speed of light is a consequence of [[Maxwell's equations]] of [[electromagnetism]]..

== General relativity ==
{{main|General relativity}}
General relativity was developed by Einstein in the years [[1907]] - [[1915]].  General relativity replaces the [[global symmetry|global]] [[Lorentz symmetry]] of special relativity with a [[local symmetry|local]] [[Lorentz symmetry]] in the presence of matter. The presence of [[matter]] "curves" [[spacetime]], and this [[curvature]] affects the path of free particles (and even the path of light). General relativity uses the mathematics of [[differential geometry]] and [[tensor]]s in order to describe [[gravitation]] as an effect of the [[geometry]] of [[spacetime]]. This theory is based on the general principle of relativity, which requires all observers to experience the same laws of physics, not just those moving with uniform speed, hence its name.

== References and links ==
See the [[Special relativity#References|special relativity references]] and the [[General relativity#References|general relativity references]]. For information on the silent film produced on this subject, see ''[[The Einstein Theory of Relativity]]''.

